#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:-1
msgid ""
"A detailed guide to the Spack spec syntax for describing package "
"constraints, including versions, variants, and dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:13
msgid "Spec Syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:15
msgid ""
"Spack has a specific syntax to describe package constraints. Each constraint "
"is individually referred to as a *spec*. Spack uses specs to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:19
msgid "Refer to a particular build configuration of a package, or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:20
msgid ""
"Express requirements, or preferences, on packages via configuration files, or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:21
msgid "Query installed packages, or buildcaches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:23
msgid ""
"Specs are more than a package name and a version; you can use them to "
"specify the compiler, compiler version, architecture, compile options, and "
"dependency options for a build. In this section, we'll go over the full "
"syntax of specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:26
msgid ""
"Here is an example of using a complex spec to install a very specific "
"configuration of ``mpileaks``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:28
msgid ""
"$ spack install mpileaks@1.2:1.4 +debug ~qt target=x86_64_v3 %gcc@15 "
"^libelf@1.1 %clang@20"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:32
msgid ""
"The figure below helps you get a sense of the various parts that compose "
"this spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:34
msgid "Spack spec with annotations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:37
msgid "When installing this, you will get:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:39
msgid ""
"The ``mpileaks`` package at some version between ``1.2`` and ``1.4`` "
"(inclusive),"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:40
msgid "with ``debug`` options enabled, and without ``qt`` support,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:41
msgid "optimized for an ``x86_64_v3`` architecture,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:42
msgid "built using ``gcc`` at version ``15``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:43
msgid ""
"depending on ``libelf`` at version ``1.1``, built with ``clang`` at version "
"``20``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:45
msgid ""
"Most specs will not be as complicated as this one, but this is a good "
"example of what is possible with specs. There are a few general rules that "
"we can already infer from this first example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:48
msgid ""
"Users can be as vague, or as specific, as they want about the details of "
"building packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:49
msgid ""
"The spec syntax is recursive, i.e. each dependency after ``%`` or ``^`` is a "
"spec itself"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:50
msgid ""
"Transitive dependencies come after the ``^`` sigil, and they always refer to "
"the root package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:51
msgid ""
"Direct dependencies come after the ``%`` sigil, and they refer either to the "
"root package, or to the last transitive dependency defined"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:53
msgid ""
"The flexibility the spec syntax offers in specifying the details of a build "
"makes Spack good for beginners and experts alike."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:58
msgid "Software Model"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:60
msgid ""
"To really understand what's going on above, we need to think about how "
"software is structured. An executable or a library generally depends on "
"other libraries in order to run. We can represent the relationship between a "
"package and its dependencies as a graph. Here is a simplified dependency "
"graph for ``mpileaks``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:84
msgid ""
"Each box above is a package, and each arrow represents a dependency on some "
"other package. For example, we say that the package ``mpileaks`` *depends "
"on* ``callpath`` and ``mpich``. ``mpileaks`` also depends *indirectly* on "
"``dyninst``, ``libdwarf``, and ``libelf``, in that these libraries are "
"dependencies of ``callpath``. To install ``mpileaks``, Spack has to build "
"all of these packages. Dependency graphs in Spack have to be acyclic, and "
"the *depends on* relationship is directional, so this is a *directed, "
"acyclic graph* or *DAG*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:90
msgid ""
"The package name identifier in the spec is the root of some dependency DAG, "
"and the DAG itself is implicit. Spack knows the precise dependencies among "
"packages, but users do not need to know the full DAG structure. Each ``^`` "
"in the full spec refers to a *transitive* dependency of the root package. "
"Each ``%`` refers to a *direct* dependency, either of the root, or of the "
"last defined transitive dependency ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:95
msgid ""
"Spack allows only a single configuration of each package, where that is "
"needed for consistency. Above, both ``mpileaks`` and ``callpath`` depend on "
"``mpich``, but ``mpich`` appears only once in the DAG. You cannot build an "
"``mpileaks`` version that depends on one version of ``mpich`` *and* on a "
"``callpath`` version that depends on some *other* version of ``mpich``. In "
"general, such a configuration would likely behave unexpectedly at runtime, "
"and Spack enforces this to ensure a consistent runtime environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:100
msgid ""
"The purpose of specs is to abstract this full DAG away from Spack users. A "
"user who does not care about the DAG at all, can refer to ``mpileaks`` by "
"simply writing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:103
msgid "mpileaks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:107
msgid ""
"The spec becomes only slightly more complicated, if that user knows that "
"``mpileaks`` indirectly uses ``dyninst`` and wants a particular version of "
"``dyninst``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:109
msgid "mpileaks ^dyninst@8.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:113
msgid ""
"Spack will fill in the rest of the details before installing the spec. The "
"user only needs to know package names and minimal details about their "
"relationship. You can put all the same modifiers on dependency specs that "
"you would put on the root spec. That is, you can specify their versions, "
"variants, and architectures just like any other spec. Specifiers are "
"associated with the nearest package name to their left."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:122
msgid "Virtual dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:124
msgid ""
"The dependency graph for ``mpileaks`` we saw above wasn't *quite* accurate. "
"``mpileaks`` uses MPI, which is an interface that has many different "
"implementations. Above, we showed ``mpileaks`` and ``callpath`` depending on "
"``mpich``, which is one *particular* implementation of MPI. However, we "
"could build either with another implementation, such as ``openmpi`` or "
"``mvapich``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:129
msgid ""
"Spack represents interfaces like this using *virtual dependencies*. The real "
"dependency DAG for ``mpileaks`` looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:153
msgid ""
"Notice that ``mpich`` has now been replaced with ``mpi``. There is no *real* "
"MPI package, but some packages *provide* the MPI interface, and these "
"packages can be substituted in for ``mpi`` when ``mpileaks`` is built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:156
msgid ""
"Spack is unique in that its virtual packages can be versioned, just like "
"regular packages. A particular version of a package may provide a particular "
"version of a virtual package. A package can *depend on* a particular version "
"of a virtual package. For instance, if an application needs MPI-2 functions, "
"it can depend on ``mpi@2:`` to indicate that it needs some implementation "
"that provides MPI-2 functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:161
msgid "Below are more details about the specifiers that you can add to specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:166
msgid "Version specifier"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:168
msgid "A version specifier"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:170
msgid "pkg@specifier"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:174
msgid ""
"comes after a package name and starts with ``@``. It can be something "
"abstract that matches multiple known versions or a specific version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:177
msgid "The version specifier usually represents *a range of versions*:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:179
msgid ""
"# All versions between v1.0 and v1.5.\n"
"# This includes any v1.5.x version\n"
"@1.0:1.5\n"
"\n"
"# All versions up to and including v3\n"
"# This would include v3.4 etc.\n"
"@:3\n"
"\n"
"# All versions above and including v4.2\n"
"@4.2:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:192
msgid "but can also be *a specific version*:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:194
msgid ""
"# Exactly version v3.2, will NOT match v3.2.1 etc.\n"
"@=3.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:200
msgid ""
"As a shorthand, ``@3`` is equivalent to the range ``@3:3`` and includes any "
"version with major version ``3``. Versions are ordered lexicographically by "
"their components. For more details on the order, see :ref:`the packaging "
"guide <version-comparison>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:204
msgid ""
"Notice that you can distinguish between the specific version ``@=3.2`` and "
"the range ``@3.2``. This is useful for packages that follow a versioning "
"scheme that omits the zero patch version number: ``3.2``, ``3.2.1``, "
"``3.2.2``, etc. In general, it is preferable to use the range syntax "
"``@3.2``, because ranges also match versions with one-off suffixes, such as "
"``3.2-custom``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:208
msgid ""
"A version specifier can also be a list of ranges and specific versions, "
"separated by commas. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:211
msgid "@1.0:1.5,=1.7.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:215
msgid ""
"matches any version in the range ``1.0:1.5`` and the specific version "
"``1.7.1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:218
msgid "Git versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:221
msgid ""
"Users wanting to just match specific commits for branch or tag based "
"versions should assign the ``commit`` variant (``commit=<40 char sha>``). "
"Spack reserves this variant specifically to track provenance of git based "
"versions. Spack will attempt to compute this value for you automatically "
"during concretization and raise a warning if it is unable to assign the "
"commit. Further details can be found in :ref:`git_version_provenance`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:227
msgid ""
"For packages with a ``git`` attribute, ``git`` references may be specified "
"instead of a numerical version (i.e., branches, tags, and commits). Spack "
"will stage and build based off the ``git`` reference provided. Acceptable "
"syntaxes for this are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:231
msgid ""
"# commit hashes\n"
"foo@abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234  # 40 character hashes are "
"automatically treated as git commits\n"
"foo@git.abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234\n"
"\n"
"# branches and tags\n"
"foo@git.develop  # use the develop branch\n"
"foo@git.0.19  # use the 0.19 tag"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:241
msgid ""
"Spack always needs to associate a Spack version with the git reference, "
"which is used for version comparison. This Spack version is heuristically "
"taken from the closest valid git tag among the ancestors of the git ref."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:244
msgid ""
"Once a Spack version is associated with a git ref, it is always printed with "
"the git ref. For example, if the commit ``@git.abcdefg`` is tagged ``0.19``, "
"then the spec will be shown as ``@git.abcdefg=0.19``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:247
msgid ""
"If the git ref is not exactly a tag, then the distance to the nearest tag is "
"also part of the resolved version. ``@git.abcdefg=0.19.git.8`` means that "
"the commit is 8 commits away from the ``0.19`` tag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:250
msgid ""
"In cases where Spack cannot resolve a sensible version from a git ref, users "
"can specify the Spack version to use for the git ref. This is done by "
"appending ``=`` and the Spack version to the git ref. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:254
msgid ""
"foo@git.my_ref=3.2 # use the my_ref tag or branch, but treat it as version "
"3.2 for version comparisons\n"
"foo@git.abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234=develop # use the given "
"commit, but treat it as develop for version comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:259
msgid ""
"Details about how versions are compared and how Spack determines if one "
"version is less than another are discussed in the developer guide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:264
msgid "Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:266
msgid ""
"Variants are named options associated with a particular package and are "
"typically used to enable or disable certain features at build time. They are "
"optional, as each package must provide default values for each variant it "
"makes available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:269
msgid ""
"The variants available for a particular package are defined by the package "
"author. ``spack info <package>`` will provide information on what build "
"variants are available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:272
msgid "There are different types of variants."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:275
msgid "Boolean Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:277
msgid ""
"Typically used to enable or disable a feature at compile time. For example, "
"a package might have a ``debug`` variant that can be explicitly enabled with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:280
msgid "+debug"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:284
msgid "and disabled with"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:286
msgid "~debug"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:291
msgid "Single-valued Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:293
msgid ""
"Often used to set defaults. For example, a package might have a "
"``compression`` variant that determines the default compression algorithm, "
"which users could set to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:296
msgid "compression=gzip"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:300
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:302
msgid "compression=zstd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:307
msgid "Multi-valued Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:309
msgid ""
"A package might have a ``fabrics`` variant that determines which network "
"fabrics to support. Users could activate multiple values at the same time. "
"For instance:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:313
msgid "fabrics=verbs,ofi"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:317
msgid ""
"enables both InfiniBand verbs and OpenFabrics interfaces. The values are "
"separated by commas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:320
msgid ""
"The meaning of ``fabrics=verbs,ofi`` is to enable *at least* the specified "
"fabrics, but other fabrics may be enabled as well. If the intent is to "
"enable *only* the specified fabrics, then the:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:323
msgid "fabrics:=verbs,ofi"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:327
msgid "syntax should be used with the ``:=`` operator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:331
msgid "Variant propagation to dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:333
msgid ""
"Spack allows variants to propagate their value to the package's dependencies "
"by using ``++``, ``--``, and ``~~`` for boolean variants. For example, for a "
"``debug`` variant:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:336
msgid ""
"mpileaks ++debug   # enabled debug will be propagated to dependencies\n"
"mpileaks +debug    # only mpileaks will have debug enabled"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:341
msgid ""
"To propagate the value of non-boolean variants Spack uses ``name==value``. "
"For example, for the ``stackstart`` variant:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:344
msgid ""
"mpileaks stackstart==4   # variant will be propagated to dependencies\n"
"mpileaks stackstart=4    # only mpileaks will have this variant value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:349
msgid ""
"Spack also allows variants to be propagated from a package that does not "
"have that variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:352
msgid "Compiler Flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:354
msgid ""
"Compiler flags are specified using the same syntax as non-boolean variants, "
"but fulfill a different purpose. While the function of a variant is set by "
"the package, compiler flags are used by the compiler wrappers to inject "
"flags into the compile line of the build. Additionally, compiler flags can "
"be inherited by dependencies by using ``==``. ``spack install libdwarf "
"cppflags==\"-g\"`` will install both libdwarf and libelf with the ``-g`` "
"flag injected into their compile line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:359
msgid ""
"Notice that the value of the compiler flags must be quoted if it contains "
"any spaces. Any of ``cppflags=-O3``, ``cppflags=\"-O3\"``, ``cppflags='-"
"O3'``, and ``cppflags=\"-O3 -fPIC\"`` are acceptable, but ``cppflags=-O3 -"
"fPIC`` is not. Additionally, if the value of the compiler flags is not the "
"last thing on the line, it must be followed by a space. The command ``spack "
"install libelf cppflags=\"-O3\"%intel`` will be interpreted as an attempt to "
"set ``cppflags=\"-O3%intel\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:364
msgid ""
"The six compiler flags are injected in the same order as implicit make "
"commands in GNU Autotools. If all flags are set, the order is ``$cppflags "
"$cflags|$cxxflags $ldflags <command> $ldlibs`` for C and C++, and ``$fflags "
"$cppflags $ldflags <command> $ldlibs`` for Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:371
msgid "Architecture specifiers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:373
msgid ""
"Each node in the dependency graph of a spec has an architecture attribute. "
"This attribute is a triplet of platform, operating system, and processor. "
"You can specify the elements either separately by using the reserved "
"keywords ``platform``, ``os``, and ``target``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:377
msgid ""
"$ spack install libelf platform=linux\n"
"$ spack install libelf os=ubuntu18.04\n"
"$ spack install libelf target=broadwell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:383
msgid ""
"Normally, users don't have to bother specifying the architecture if they are "
"installing software for their current host, as in that case the values will "
"be detected automatically. If you need fine-grained control over which "
"packages use which targets (or over *all* packages' default target), see :"
"ref:`package-preferences`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:391
msgid "Support for specific microarchitectures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:393
msgid ""
"Spack knows how to detect and optimize for many specific microarchitectures "
"and encodes this information in the ``target`` portion of the architecture "
"specification. A complete list of the microarchitectures known to Spack can "
"be obtained in the following way:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:398
msgid ""
"When a spec is installed, Spack matches the compiler being used with the "
"microarchitecture being targeted to inject appropriate optimization flags at "
"compile time. Giving a command such as the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:401
msgid "$ spack install zlib target=icelake %gcc@14"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:405
msgid "will produce compilation lines similar to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:407
msgid ""
"$ /usr/bin/gcc-14 -march=icelake-client -mtune=icelake-client -c ztest10532."
"c\n"
"$ /usr/bin/gcc-14 -march=icelake-client -mtune=icelake-client -c -fPIC -O2 "
"ztest10532.\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:413
msgid ""
"where the flags ``-march=icelake-client -mtune=icelake-client`` are injected "
"by Spack based on the requested target and compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:415
msgid ""
"If Spack determines that the requested compiler cannot optimize for the "
"requested target or cannot build binaries for that target at all, it will "
"exit with a meaningful error message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:417
msgid ""
"$ spack install zlib target=icelake %gcc@5\n"
"==> Error: cannot produce optimized binary for micro-architecture "
"\"icelake\" with gcc@5.5.0 [supported compiler versions are 8:]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:422
msgid ""
"Conversely, if an older compiler is selected for a newer microarchitecture, "
"Spack will optimize for the best match instead of failing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:424
msgid ""
"$ spack arch\n"
"linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell\n"
"\n"
"$ spack spec zlib%gcc@4.8\n"
"Input spec\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib%gcc@4.8\n"
"\n"
"Concretized\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.11%gcc@4.8+optimize+pic+shared arch=linux-ubuntu18.04-haswell\n"
"\n"
"$ spack spec zlib%gcc@9.0.1\n"
"Input spec\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib%gcc@9.0.1\n"
"\n"
"Concretized\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.11%gcc@9.0.1+optimize+pic+shared arch=linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:447
msgid ""
"In the snippet above, for instance, the microarchitecture was demoted to "
"``haswell`` when compiling with ``gcc@4.8`` because support to optimize for "
"``broadwell`` starts from ``gcc@4.9:``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:449
msgid ""
"Finally, if Spack has no information to match the compiler and target, it "
"will proceed with the installation but avoid injecting any microarchitecture-"
"specific flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:455
msgid "Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:457
msgid ""
"Each node in a DAG can specify dependencies using either the ``%`` or the "
"``^`` sigil:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:459
msgid ""
"The ``%`` sigil identifies direct dependencies, which means there must be an "
"edge connecting the dependency to the node they refer to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:460
msgid ""
"The ``^`` sigil identifies transitive dependencies, which means the "
"dependency just needs to be in the sub-DAG of the node they refer to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:462
msgid ""
"The order of transitive dependencies does not matter when writing a spec. "
"For example, these two specs represent exactly the same configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:465
msgid ""
"mpileaks ^callpath@1.0 ^libelf@0.8.3\n"
"mpileaks ^libelf@0.8.3 ^callpath@1.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:470
msgid ""
"Direct dependencies specified with ``%`` apply either to the most recent "
"transitive dependency (``^``), or, if none, to the root package in the spec. "
"So in the spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:473
msgid "root %dep1 ^transitive %dep2 %dep3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:477
msgid ""
"``dep1`` is a direct dependency of ``root``, while both ``dep2`` and "
"``dep3`` are direct dependencies of ``transitive``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:480
msgid "Constraining virtual packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:482
msgid ""
"When installing a package that depends on a virtual package, see :ref:`sec-"
"virtual-dependencies`, you can opt to specify the particular provider you "
"want to use, or you can let Spack pick. For example, if you just type this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:485
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:489
msgid ""
"Then Spack will pick an ``mpi`` provider for you according to site policies. "
"If you really want a particular version, say ``mpich``, then you could run "
"this instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:492
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks ^mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:496
msgid ""
"This forces Spack to use some version of ``mpich`` for its implementation. "
"As always, you can be even more specific and require a particular ``mpich`` "
"version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:499
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks ^mpich@3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:503
msgid ""
"The ``mpileaks`` package in particular only needs MPI-1 commands, so any MPI "
"implementation will do. If another package depends on ``mpi@2`` and you try "
"to give it an insufficient MPI implementation (e.g., one that provides only "
"``mpi@:1``), then Spack will raise an error. Likewise, if you try to plug in "
"some package that doesn't provide MPI, Spack will raise an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:510
msgid "Explicit binding of virtual dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:512
msgid ""
"There are packages that provide more than just one virtual dependency. When "
"interacting with them, users might want to utilize just a subset of what "
"they could provide and use other providers for virtuals they need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:515
msgid ""
"It is possible to be more explicit and tell Spack which dependency should "
"provide which virtual, using a special syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:517
msgid "$ spack spec strumpack ^mpi=intel-parallel-studio+mkl ^lapack=openblas"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:521
msgid "Concretizing the spec above produces the following DAG:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:525
msgid ""
"where ``intel-parallel-studio`` *could* provide ``mpi``, ``lapack``, and "
"``blas`` but is used only for the former. The ``lapack`` and ``blas`` "
"dependencies are satisfied by ``openblas``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:529
msgid "Dependency edge attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:531
msgid ""
"Some specs require additional information about the relationship between a "
"package and its dependency. This information lives on the edge between the "
"two, and can be specified by following the dependency sigil with square-"
"brackets ``[]``. Edge attributes are always specified as key-value pairs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:535
msgid "root ^[key=value] dep"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:539
msgid ""
"In the following sections we'll discuss the edge attributes that are "
"currently allowed in the spec syntax."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:542
msgid "Virtuals"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:544
msgid ""
"Packages can provide, or depend on, multiple virtual packages. Users can "
"select which virtuals to use from which dependency by specifying the "
"``virtuals`` edge attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:547
msgid "$ spack install mpich %[virtuals=c,cxx] clang %[virtuals=fortran] gcc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:551
msgid ""
"The command above tells Spack to use ``clang`` to provide the ``c`` and "
"``cxx`` virtuals, and ``gcc`` to provide the ``fortran`` virtual."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:553
msgid ""
"The special syntax we have seen in :ref:`explicit-binding-virtuals` is a "
"more compact way to specify the ``virtuals`` edge attribute. For instance, "
"an equivalent formulation of the command above is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:556
msgid "$ spack install mpich %c,cxx=clang %fortran=gcc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:561
msgid "Conditional dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:563
msgid ""
"Conditional dependencies allow dependency constraints to be applied only "
"under certain conditions. We can express conditional constraints by "
"specifying the ``when`` edge attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:566
msgid "$ spack install hdf5 ^[when=+mpi] mpich@3.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:570
msgid ""
"This tells Spack that hdf5 should depend on ``mpich@3.1`` if it is "
"configured with MPI support."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:573
msgid "Dependency propagation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:575
msgid ""
"The dependency specifications on a node, can be propagated using a double "
"percent ``%%`` sigil. This is particularly useful when specifying compilers. "
"For instance, the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:579
msgid "$ spack install hdf5+cxx+fortran %%c,cxx=clang %%fortran=gfortran"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:583
msgid ""
"tells Spack to install ``hdf5`` using Clang as the C and C++ compiler, and "
"GCC as the Fortran compiler. It also tells Spack to propagate the same "
"choices, as :ref:`strong preferences <package-strong-preferences>`,  to the "
"runtime sub-DAG of ``hdf5``. Build tools are unaffected and can still prefer "
"to use a different compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:588
msgid "Specifying Specs by Hash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:590
msgid ""
"Complicated specs can become cumbersome to enter on the command line, "
"especially when many of the qualifications are necessary to distinguish "
"between similar installs. To avoid this, when referencing an existing spec, "
"Spack allows you to reference specs by their hash. We previously discussed "
"the spec hash that Spack computes. In place of a spec in any command, "
"substitute ``/<hash>`` where ``<hash>`` is any amount from the beginning of "
"a spec hash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:595
msgid ""
"For example, let's say that you accidentally installed two different "
"``mvapich2`` installations. If you want to uninstall one of them but don't "
"know what the difference is, you can run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:598
msgid ""
"$ spack find --long mvapich2\n"
"==> 2 installed packages.\n"
"-- linux-centos7-x86_64 / gcc@6.3.0 ----------\n"
"qmt35td mvapich2@2.2%gcc\n"
"er3die3 mvapich2@2.2%gcc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:607
msgid "You can then uninstall the latter installation using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:609
msgid "$ spack uninstall /er3die3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:614
msgid ""
"Or, if you want to build with a specific installation as a dependency, you "
"can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:616
msgid "$ spack install trilinos ^/er3die3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:621
msgid ""
"If the given spec hash is sufficiently long as to be unique, Spack will "
"replace the reference with the spec to which it refers. Otherwise, it will "
"prompt for a more qualified hash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:624
msgid ""
"Note that this will not work to reinstall a dependency uninstalled by "
"``spack uninstall --force``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:627
msgid "Specs on the command line"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:629
msgid ""
"The characters used in the spec syntax were chosen to work well with most "
"shells. However, there are cases where the shell may interpret the spec "
"before Spack gets a chance to parse it, leading to unexpected results. Here "
"we document two such cases, and how to avoid them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:634
msgid "Unix shells"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:636
msgid ""
"On Unix-like systems, the shell may expand ``~foo`` to the home directory of "
"a user named ``foo``, so Spack won't see it as a :ref:`disabled boolean "
"variant <basic-variants>` ``foo``. To work around this without quoting, you "
"can avoid whitespace between the package name and boolean variants:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:639
msgid ""
"mpileaks ~debug   # shell may expand this to `mpileaks /home/debug`\n"
"mpileaks~debug    # use this instead"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:644
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can use a hyphen ``-`` character to disable a variant, "
"but be aware that this *requires* a space between the package name and the "
"variant:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:646
msgid ""
"mpileaks-debug     # wrong: refers to a package named \"mpileaks-debug\"\n"
"mpileaks -debug    # right: refers to a package named mpileaks with debug "
"disabled"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:651
msgid ""
"As a last resort, ``debug=False`` can also be used to disable a boolean "
"variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:654
msgid "Windows CMD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:656
msgid ""
"In Windows CMD, the caret ``^`` is an escape character, and needs itself "
"escaping. Similarly, the equals ``=`` character has special meaning in CMD."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:659
msgid ""
"To use the caret and equals characters in a spec, you can quote and escape "
"them like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:661
msgid "C:\\> spack install mpileaks \"^^libelf\" \"foo=bar\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spec_syntax.rst:665
msgid ""
"These issues are not present in PowerShell. See GitHub issue `#42833 "
"<https://github.com/spack/spack/issues/42833>`_ and `#43348 <https://github."
"com/spack/spack/issues/43348>`_ for more details."
msgstr ""
